Review the following code and explain why it's an anti-pattern, then rewrite it to avoid hitting governor limits:

for (Account acc : accounts) {
    List<Contact> cons = [SELECT Id FROM Contact WHERE AccountId = :acc.Id];
    // ... process cons
}

output:
Issuing a SOQL query inside a for loop runs once per iteration. With more than 100 Accounts in 'accounts', this exceeds the governor limit of 100 SOQL queries per transaction (and a similar issue applies if DML is inside the loop). The fix is to collect all the Ids first, run a single query for all related Contacts, group the results into a Map, then iterate:

Set<Id> accountIds = new Set<Id>();
for (Account acc : accounts) {
    accountIds.add(acc.Id);
}

Map<Id, List<Contact>> contactsByAccountId = new Map<Id, List<Contact>>();
for (Contact con : [SELECT Id, AccountId FROM Contact WHERE AccountId IN :accountIds]) {
    if (!contactsByAccountId.containsKey(con.AccountId)) {
        contactsByAccountId.put(con.AccountId, new List<Contact>());
    }
    contactsByAccountId.get(con.AccountId).add(con);
}

for (Account acc : accounts) {
    List<Contact> cons = contactsByAccountId.get(acc.Id);
    // ... process cons
}
